# SLA Monitoring Standards

This document defines standards for monitoring data pipeline SLAs, freshness targets, and alerting.

---

## SLA Definitions

### Freshness SLA

| Dataset Category | Freshness Target | Grace Period | Escalation |
|-----------------|------------------|--------------|------------|
| Real-time streams | < 5 minutes | 5 minutes | Page on-call |
| Hourly batches | < 1 hour | 15 minutes | Slack alert |
| Daily batches | < 4 hours past midnight | 1 hour | Slack alert |
| Weekly reports | < 24 hours | 4 hours | Email |

### Completeness SLA

| Dataset Category | Completeness Target | Monitoring |
|-----------------|--------------------|-----------| 
| Transaction data | 99.9% | Row count vs expected |
| Event streams | 99.5% | Sequence gap detection |
| Aggregated reports | 100% | Partition presence check |

---

## Monitoring Implementation

### Freshness Check

```python
from datetime import datetime, timedelta

def check_freshness(
    dataset: str,
    max_age: timedelta,
    get_latest_timestamp: callable,
) -> dict:
    latest = get_latest_timestamp(dataset)
    age = datetime.utcnow() - latest
    is_fresh = age <= max_age

    return {
        "dataset": dataset,
        "latest_timestamp": latest.isoformat(),
        "age_seconds": age.total_seconds(),
        "sla_seconds": max_age.total_seconds(),
        "status": "ok" if is_fresh else "breach",
    }
```

### Row Count Monitoring

```python
def check_row_count(
    dataset: str,
    partition: str,
    expected_min: int,
    expected_max: int,
    actual_count: int,
) -> dict:
    status = "ok"
    if actual_count < expected_min:
        status = "low"
    elif actual_count > expected_max:
        status = "high"

    return {
        "dataset": dataset,
        "partition": partition,
        "actual": actual_count,
        "expected_range": f"[{expected_min}, {expected_max}]",
        "status": status,
    }
```

