## Alerting Tiers

| Tier | Condition | Channel | Response Time |
|------|-----------|---------|---------------|
| P1 - Critical | Revenue-impacting pipeline down | Page on-call | 15 minutes |
| P2 - High | SLA breach on critical dataset | Slack + ticket | 1 hour |
| P3 - Medium | SLA breach on non-critical dataset | Slack | 4 hours |
| P4 - Low | Warning threshold crossed | Dashboard | Next business day |

### Alert Fatigue Prevention

- [ ] Alerts fire only on actionable conditions
- [ ] Duplicate alerts are suppressed (deduplicated within window)
- [ ] Alerts include enough context to diagnose (dataset, partition, expected vs actual)
- [ ] Alerts link to runbook with troubleshooting steps
- [ ] Alert thresholds are reviewed quarterly

---

## Dashboard Requirements

### Pipeline Health Dashboard

| Panel | Content |
|-------|---------|
| Pipeline status | Green/yellow/red for each pipeline |
| Freshness heatmap | Time since last update per dataset |
| SLA compliance | Percentage of SLA met over rolling 30 days |
| Error trends | Error count over time |
| Processing duration | P50/P95 pipeline duration over time |

---

## Escalation Procedures

```
Alert fires -> Check dashboard -> Consult runbook -> Fix or escalate

If not resolved in:
  15 min (P1) -> Escalate to team lead
  1 hour (P2) -> Escalate to team lead
  4 hours (P3) -> Escalate to engineering manager
```

---

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Correct Approach |
|--------------|--------------|------------------|
| Alert on every failure | Alert fatigue | Alert on SLA breach only |
| No context in alerts | Can't diagnose | Include dataset, partition, values |
| No runbook linked | Slow resolution | Link runbook in every alert |
| Static thresholds | False positives on weekends | Time-aware thresholds |
